But now more particularly, we may observe what the Prophet says in his Complaint and Prayer to GOD. We have first that petition, Give bred to me, O LORD, He had before complain'd that the People whom he preach'd unto, were resolv'd to give 〈◊〉 unto him. MEN wou'd not hear the World from his mouth, nor give heed to his Preaching: however, he trusts that GOD will have regard to this labour of Love, and accept him in it. NOTE, It is matter of comfort to faithful Ministers, that thô 〈…〉 & despite their Preaching, yet they may hope that GOD will accept & 〈◊〉
their Endeavours;
and thô Israel be not gathered, yet their Reward is with GOD.—Or, Men wou'd not take notice of his Grievances, and do him Justice: he therefore applies himself to GOD, who is a Refuge for the Oppressed; and refers his Cause to him, who is an upright Judge. 〈◊〉 d. Thô men will not receive my Complaints; yet LORD, do then admit them, and judge between me & my adversaries: Hearken to the voice of them that contend with me; hear how clamorous they are in their false Accusations, and appear for my vindication; take notice of all their Rage & Spite, and take me under thy Protection; Let them be blasted in their cruel Designs & Wicked Attempts; let them be confounded & dismayed; but let not me be confounded nor dismayed Jer.17.18. .
